{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600544/1930111101/0385.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nHOOVO STRESSES\n1 COURTADHERENCE\nAlso Urges Broad Participa\nHon by U. S. in Efforts\nToward World Peace.\n(Continued From First Page.)\nSoldier in Arlington Cemetery and a\nmemorial service in the auditorium\nwith selections by the Marine Band.\nThe principal address at the Arling\nton ceremony, at which Rev. Dr. James\nI. Vance of Nashville, Tenn., presided,\nwas by Prof. Parker T. Moon of Colum\nbia University.\n\u201cModern war,\u201d Prof. Moon declared,\n\u201cis not the spontaneous expression of\nhuman instinct, nor even necessarily\nthe outcome of deliberate malice, but\nmay be merely the grotesque but\nghastly result of diplomatic blunders.\nIn 1914 European governments con\ncealed their mistakes by falsifying and\nediting the blunders. Organized prop\naganda was necessary to maintain\nmorale at the point where millions of\nmen could kill millions of other men\nwhom they had never before seen and\nwith whom they had no personal quar\nrel.\nSpurious Substitute.\n\u201cThere is a path which leads from\nJingoism and saber-rattling to patriot\nism and, peace. Jingoism exists among\ncertain factions and parties the world\nover, and we are not without some\nshare of it. It is a compound of bluff,\nbluster and braggadocio. It is the spirit\nof those who believe that a nation to\nbe respected must act the part of a\nbraggart and bully. That spirit is a\nspurious substitute for patriotism. It is\nsingularly out of place in America, we\nhave too much power to boast of it, or\nto abuse it.\u201d\nEventual adherence of the United\nStates to the World Court was pre\ndicted by Prof. Phillip C. Jessup at the\nround-table discussion of the alliance\ntoday.\n\u201cThe World Court Is not a dead issue\nin the United States and will not be,\u2019\u2019\nhe said, \u201cuntil the Senate has consented\nto ratification of the protocol which\nwould permit the United States to take\nits place in supporting the only effec\ntive permanent international tribunal.\nPolitical opposition may delay, but will\nnot prevent, such participation. Noth\ning has yet occurred, or seems likely\nto occur, which would alter the view of\nthe majority of the people of the United\nStates as expressed by four Presidents\nand a majority oi the Senate and House\nof Representatives.\"\n\"A thousand dollars put into giving\niome destitute Chinese a chance to make\na modest living will Jo more to bring\nabout order in that country than mil\nlions of words about theories of govern\nment or the beauties of unselfish pa\ntriotism,\u201d said Grover Clark, associate\ndirector of the International Chinese\nRelief Commission.\nThe only guarantee of world peace,\nwith fear-ridden nations resorting to\never costlier and more destructive\narmaments, will be a \u201cuniversal asso\nciation of nations,\" including the United\nStates, Arthur Meighen. former prime\nminister of Canada, declared at a ban\nquet here last nigbt to the Good-Will\nCongress. t\nHe painted a gloomy picture of tne\nprospects of security through arma\nment, and of the destructiveness of an\nother war to an audience which in\ncluded diplomatic representatives of\n38 nations.\n\u201cThere is manifestly nothing in ef\nfect now which goes far enough, Mr-\nMeighan declared, \u201cfor armaments still\nkeep up and grow larger every day.\n\u201cWe are a long way yet from being\norganized against war though we know,\nif we know anything, that the one su\npremely Important task before our\nworld today is to bring about that\norganization. Such an organization\ncannot be brought about without the\nUnited States.\nRealizing the historic disinclination\nof the United States to depart from\nthe policy of \u201cno entangling alli\nances,\u201d Mr. Meighen insisted that a\nphrase coined to describe an eighteenth\ncentury peril \u201cshould not be used now\nto prevent that co-operation by which\n\u2022lone we can escape a far greater peril\nin the twentieth century.\"\nHe insisted that the League of Na\ntions\u2019 definition of an aggressor State\ncan actually be applied, however diffi\ncult the application may be, and actually\nworked in preventing a Greco-Bulgarian\nwar in 1925.\nEnemies Within Frontiers.\nAlanson B. Houghton, former Ambas\nsador to Great Britain and Germany,\nstressed understanding of other peoples\nas essential for world peace. Interna\ntional differences, he said, are as certain\nto arise as differences between indi\nviduals. He denounced those people at\nwork within the United States, as well\nas other nations, to stir up ill will i\n\u2022gainst the rest of the world.\n\u201cThe enemies of peace here in Amer\nica,\u201d he said, \u201care not so much those\nwithout our frontiers as those within\nthose who foster hate arid create suspi\ncion and stir up distrust. Our relations\nwith foreign nations, like charity, really\nbegin at home. We make them largely\nwhat we will. They are not made for us\nby others.\n\u201cGood will, which must be mutual If\nfair and honorable settlements are to be\nattained, is not possession of any one\npeople. Certainly, we here in America\npossess no monopoly of it.\u201d\nThe United States, its objections\nhaving been met, no longer has any\nexcuse for remaining out of the World\nCourt, said Jacob Gould Schurman,\nformer Ambassador to Germany.\n\u201cIt is the judicial organ of the civ\nilised world,\u201d he said. \u201cI can thunk\nof no international Institution which\nshould appeal more strongly to the\nAmerican sense of law and justice or\nwhich harmonizes more strikingly with\nthe fundamental principles of American\nforeign policy,\n\u201cLook again at the peace pact. Ex\nperience has already shown that when\nnations fail into a dispute they forget\nIt. It should be the business of a duly\nconstituted committee to remind the\nquarreling signatories of the peace pact\nof the obligations which they have as\nsumed.\n\u201cIt was left to Americr., on the oc\ncasion of the difference between So\nviet Russia and China not long ago to\nassume that important vicarious roie.\nThat is an unfair burden for us to un\ndertake.\u201d\nThe Kellogg pact can be made an\neffective force by \"perfecting perma\nnent machinery for adjudication of\ncontroversy and by enactment of inter\nnational law in all important fields in\nwhich custom and treaty have not so\nfar established binding rules of con\nduct between nations.\u201d said Judge Flor\nence E. Allen of the Ohio Supreme\nCourt.\n\u201cThe mind of the race,\u201d she said,\n\u201cfor the first time In history has met\nupon the proposition that the sover\neignty shall renounce its sovereign privi\nlege to do wrong.\u201d\nThe banquet brought to a close a day\nof group meetings and reports from!\nofficers of the alliance. There has never\nbeen more cynicism regarding the possi\nbility of peace than today. Dr. Henry A.\nAtkinson, general secretary, reported.\nHie last meeting of the League Assem\nbly, be said, was marked notably by\nthe absence of the spirit of hope which\nhas characterized other sessions.\nA permanent disarmament confer\nence, meeting at two or three year in\ntervals, with an international secretariat\nwas urged by Prof. James T. Shotwell\nof Columbia University, who said that\nGreat Britain is advancing this pro\nposal at Geneva.\nLieut. Van Winkle Improving.\nLieut. Mina Van Winkle, head of\nthe Woman\u2019s Bureau og the Police\nDepartment, was reported as much im\nproved today following an operation\nyesterday at the hospital of Dr. Howard\nKelley in Baltimore.\nText of Hoover Speech\nArmistice Address Affirms Move for International\nPeace Pacts and Emphasizes America\u2019s\nInterests as World-Wide.\nThe full text of President Hoover\u2019s\nArmistice day address follows:\nUpon this day all thoughts must turn\nto our heroic dead whose lives were\ngiven in defense of the liberties and\nideals of our country. Their contri\nbution to these priceless heritages was\nmad; without reservation; they gave\nthe full measure of their intelligence\nand energy and enthusiasm, and life\nitself, forfeiting their portion of fur\nther happiness\u2014all that we and out\nchildren might live on more safely,\nmore happily and more assured of the\nprecious blessings of security and peace.\nA solemn obligation lies upon us to\npress forward in our pursuit of those\nthings for which they died. Our duty\nis to seek ever new and widening op\nportunities to insure the world against\nthe horror and irretrievable wastage of\nwar. Much has been done, but we must\nwage peace continuously, with the same\nenergy as they waged war.\nThis year 1930 has been rendered\nnotable in peace annals in the achieve\nment of the London Naval Treaty. That\nhas disposed of one of those major fric\ntions among the great naval powers\u2014\nthat Is, competition in naval construc\ntion \u2014and it has made a sensible ad\nvance in the reduction of warships.\nPotential Contticts Brew.\nThe promotion of peace and preven\ntion of war, however, cannot rest upon\nthe accomplishments of any one year.\nThe outlook for peace is happier than\nfor half a century, yet we cannot over\nlook the fact that nations in many\nways are always potentially in conflict.\nThere are not only the accumulated\nag-old controversies and ambitions\nwhich are alive with prejudice, emotion\nand passion, but you may be assured\nthat there will always be an unceasing\ncrop of new controversies between na\ntions.\nEvery shif in power, every advance\nin communication, in trade and finance\ndailv increases the points of contact of\none nation with another. The diffusion\nof their citizens and their property\nabroad increasingly penetrates and\noverlaps into the four corners of the\nearth. The many inventions of these\ncitizens, their ceaseless energies, bring\nan hourly grist to our foreign\noffices of contested right or grievance.\nIt is true that many of these contacts\nmake for understanding and good will:\nit is indeed of the first importance to\npeace that th;se happy influences be\ncultivated, and that the unhappy ones\nbe disposed of with justice and good\nwill.\nThe Kellogg-Briand pact, signed a\nlittle over two years ago to further\nsafeguard against the dangers f\nthese conflicts, has already become a\npowerful influence in international af\nfairs Several further states have ad\nt red to it since last November, bring\ning the total number of nations up to\n58 which have renounced war as an\ninstrument of national policy and have\nagreed to settle conflicts of whatever\nnature by pacific means. Five other\nstates have expressed an intention to\nadhere, which will bring the total to 63.\na figure comprising all but two nat.ons.\nMoral Restraint Factor.\nBy the recognition of this fundamen\ntal principle of peace and from the\nmoral restraint that the covenant it\nself presents this agreement has be\ncome one of the most potent instru\nments for peace which the world has\never forged for itself.\nThere has been much discussion as to\nthe desirability of some further exten\nsion of the pact so as to effect a double\npurpose of assuring methodical develop\nment of this machinery of peaceful set\ntlement and to insure at least the mo\nbilization of world opinion against those\nwho fail when strain comes. I do not\nsay that some such further step may\nnot some day come about.\nSuch a formula w'ould be stimulative\nand would appeal to the dramatic sense\nof the world as a mark in the progress\nof peace. But less dramatic and possi\nbly even more sure is the day-to-day\nstrengthening and buttressing of the\npact by extension from one nation to\nanother of treaties which in times of\nfriction assure resort to well tried proc\nesses of competent, negotiation, of con\nciliation and of arbitration.\nAnd we can in our own relations re\ncord great advancement in these funda\nmental but less dramatic su-xirts to\nthe pact during the two years since Its\nsignature. Up to the signature of the\npact our country was bound by arbi\ntration treaties to seven other nations.\nIt was bound to 26 nations by concilia\ntion treaties, both bilateral and multi\nlateral. Since that time we have com\npleted treaties with 15 more countries,\nand ip addition we have signed further\n1 arbitration and conciliation treaties\nwith 45 nations, of which 26 have been\nratified and the others are either before\nthe Senate or in course of presentation\nto it.\nConciliation Is Pledged.\nBy these treaties of arbitration we\npledged ourselves to the acceptance\nof the judgment of a disinterested\nthird party in all controversies of a\njusticiable character. By treaties of con\nciliation we Diedge oi\u201d selves to submit\nall other types of controversy to nego\ntiations or the mediation of commis\nsions which embrace representatives of\ndisinterested nations.\nIt is our purpose to develop in every\nwav the use of arbitration and con-1\nciliation agreements in our relations\nwith forei tTr nations.\nOther rations of the world have like\nwise been engaged over years in the\nbuilding up of the machinery for pa\ncific settlement of controversies. There\nare hundreds of arbitration and concill\nation treaties existing directly between\nRADIO SALES TALKS\nFOUND UNPOPULAR\nIN 6-MONTH SURVEY\niQniinu.d From First Ptgf)\nthere are aristocrats among the broad\ncasters whose programs get over to the\npublic well and whose advertising op\nportunities are recognized, while others\nare not so successful.\u201d\nCroasley, Inc., headed by A. M. Cross\nley, is conducting radio survey princi\npally at the behest of the National Ad-\nI vertisers, Inc., which latter organiza\ntion is sponsoring the survey. Forty\nseven members of the association have\nprovided about $35,000 to make the\nstudy, and Crossley. Inc has a few\nprivate clients outside of the associa\ntion.\nThe survey is being conducted with\nrepresentatives in the principal broad\ncast centers of the country, listening\nI to all manner of radio programs and\nthrough questionnaires, which so far\nhave gone out to 32,000 and will have\nbeen presented to 10,000 when the year\u2019s\nsurvey is completed.\nThe principal question asked radio\nlisteners, of course, is whether they have\nconsciously bought anything as a result\nof radio advertising. The questionnaire\nasked that a product be named U the\nanswer is yes. Mr. Karol reported that\nabout 25 per cent of those questioned\nanswered in the affirmative and named\nproducts. Little, he said, is to be gained\nso far from those answers, various\nfactors entering into the final analysis\nof this phase of the survey.\nThere is. however, he said, no doubt\nin the minds of those conducting the\n1 survey that the radio listener does not\nwant to hear advertising and salesman\nship from the loudspeaker in his home,\ni The surveyors have found that this\ni difficulty of getting the advertising\nmessage across to the listener la solved\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON*, D. C. t TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 11, lIW.\nthem. Indeed, the covenant of the\nLeague of Nations provides for arbi\ntration and concllatlon amongst 54 na\ntions of the world.\nIt is my belief that the world will\nhave become firmly interlocked wlih\nsuch agreements within a very few\nyears and that It will become an ac\ncepted principle of international law\nthat disputes between nations which It\nhas not been possible to determine\nthrough the ordinary channels of di\nplomacy shall in future be submitted to\narbitration or to international concilia\ntion commissions.\nWorld Court Fanctions.\nIn the development of methods of\npacific settlement, a great hope lies in\never extending the body and principles\nof international law on which such set\ntlements will be based. The World\nCourt is now a strongly established in\nstitution amongst 45 nations as a con\ntinuing body, performing and facilitat\ning justiciable determinations which\ncan only be accomplished sporadically\nunder special treaties of arbitration. Its\n1 permanence is assured, and from it\nthere is steadily growing a body of\nprecedent, decisions and acceptance of\nlaw in the formulation of which we\nshould have a part, not alone in our\nown interest, but in advancement of\npeace.\nA year ago I made a suggestion of a\npractical contribution in settlement of\nan age-old controversy of freedom of\nthe seas. I proposed that food supplies\nshould be made immune from inter\nference in time of war and that the\nsecurity of supplies should be guaran\nj teed by neutral transport and manage\nment. I proposed it not alone upon\nhumane grounds, but that the haunt\ning fears of nations who must live from\nover the sea might be relaxed and the\nsacrifices which they make for naval\nstrength might be lessened. Our food\nsupplies are assured, and it is therefore\nfrom us a disinterested proposal. It\nwould make for prevention as well as\nlimitation of war.\nWe, as a Nation whose independ\nence, liberties and securities were bom\nof war. cannot contend that there\nnever Is or never will be righteous\ncause for war in the world. Nor can\nwe assume that righteousness has so\nadvanced in the world that we may\nyet have complete confidence in the full\ngrowth of pacific means or rest solely\nupon the processes of peace fo* detente.\nU. S. Has World Interests.\nWith the progress the world has\nmade in the installation of the me\nthcdical processes for the settlement\nof controversies, the largei problem\n1 emerges as to fidelity to agreement to\nU se these methods. The thought and\nanxiety of the world la Erected\nto the question as to what the nations\nof the world will do in case of a failure\nto use them. It is useless forusto\nsay that we have no interest in such\nC 'Since our experience in the World\nWar no one will deny the dangers which\nfnrpien wars bring to our shores or the\ntoteSt we must have in the peace of\nthe world at large. But Ido not hold\nthat our obligation in these matters lies\nwholly on the basis of self-interest. it\nLs upon its moral and spiritual strength\nthat the advancement of the world must\nOur basis of co-operation to Preserve\npeace among nations must be differen\nfrom that of the other great nations of\nthe world. The security of our geo\ngraphic situation, our traditional free\ndom from entanglements in the involved\n1 diplomacy of Europe, and our disinter\nestedness enables us to give a different\nand in many ways a more effective serv\nice to peace.\nPacific Aid Pledged.\nThe nations of Europe, bordered as\nthey are by age-old dangers of which\nwe in the Western Hemisphere have lit\ntle appreciation, beset as they ere by\nlong-inherited fears, believe that they\nmust subscribe to methods which in the\nlast resort will use force to compel na\ntions to abide by their agreements to\nsettle controversies by pacific means.\nWe, in our great state of safety and in\ndependence, should make no criticism\nof their conclusions which arise from\ntheir necessities.\nBut we believe that our contribution\ncan best be made in these emergencies,\nwhen nations fail to keep their under\ntakings of pacific settlement of disputes,\nby our good offices and helpfulness, free\nfrom any advance commitment or en\ntanglement as to the character of our\naction.\nThe purpose of our Government is to\nco-operate with others, to use our,\nfriendly offices, and, short of any im-\nplication of the use of force, to use\nevery friendly effort and all good will\nto maintain the peace of the world.\nThe war that ended on this day 12\nyears ago taught us one thing, if noth\ning else, and that is the blessing of\npeace. When we look back upon its\nsplendid valor and heroism then dis\ni played, when we remember the mag\nnifleent energies poured forth by young\nand old. when we recall the marvelous\ni exercises of the greatest virtues that\nelorify the human race\u2014unselfishness,\n-sacrifice, co-operation, both by men\nand* women\u2014we are looking not upon\nqualities which war creates, but rather\nupon the traits of the human race\nwhich war makes seem more vivid by\ncontrast with its own horrors. These\nsame qualities are exercised, but are un-\nI sung and unheralded in times of peace.\nI Those who died displaying them would\nI have displayed them living and would\n1 have wrought their fruits into the en\nduring fabric of our peaceful destiny.\nWe can only pledge ourselves, in honor\nof their memory, to the task of making\never more unlikely that our youth here\nafter shall be denied its opportunity to\ndevote its idealism and Its energies to\nthe constructive arts of peace.\nto some extent by attractiveness and\nsubtlety in the announcer reading the\nadvertising message into the rest of the\nprogram. But, he declared, radio lis\nteners want music, more music and are\nImpatient when the advertising matter\ni in the broadcast take- up the time that\n1 might be allotted to music. Further\nmore, he said, there is a definite and\nj very limited amount of time the an\nnmincer may devote to his advertising\nI message. In programs of any length\nI the advertising matter should get across\nin a minute or less.\nGoods sold with a large turnover.\nI easily obtainable at all points and\nwhose radio advertising is principally\ni to get the public \u201cname conscious\u2019 pro- j\nfits better by radio advertising than\nl goods which require long selling talks\nThe public, he said, won\u2019t listen to these\n1 long-selling talks. j\nt \u201cHowever,\u201d he said, \u201cyou can readily\ni gee that 5,000.000 circulation ls not\nsmall. Os course, it is said only once\nand if it is not caught it is lost.\u201d\nMr. Karol and Mr. Crossley will take j\nthe members of the Advertisers\u2019 Asso\nciation behind the scenes of their sur-,\nvex at the radio dinner tonight and\ngive them a complete report of the\ni first six months\u2019 work of the survey\nThe dinner meeting will be open only\nto members of the association.\nLee H. Bristol of the Bristol-Myers\nCo. of New York, was elected president\nof the Association of National Adver\ntisers, Inc., at the morning session.\nHe succeeds Bernard Lichtenberg,\nvice president of the Alexander Ham\nilton Institute. Mr. Bristol was elevated\nfrom the vice presidency.\nThis morning\u2019s session was given\nover to the receipt of reports from\nvarious committees on their work during\nthe year and the report of President 1\nLichtenberg.\nElection of officers and directors con\nsumed most of the session.\nStuart Peabody was elected to fill the\nvice presidency left vacant by Bristol\nand w. A. Grove waa re-elected to the\nother vice presidency. P. J. Kelly was\nelected managing director and aeere\ntary-treasuraa.\nHOOVER\u2019S SILENCE\nON PROTOCOL CITED\nArmistice Day Address Re\ngarded as Significant in\nThings Left Unsaid.\nBY FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE.\nPresident Hoover's Armistice day\npeech this morning at the annual con\nference and good-will congress of the\nWorld Alliance for International Friend\nship Through the Churches was mainly\nsignificant for what it did not say. In\nthe first place, the President conspicu\nously refrained from indicating any in\ntention of asking the Senate to ratify\nthe United States\u2019 signature to the\nWorld Court protocol. That omission\nbrings keen disappointment to the more\nardent supporters of the American\npeace movement, especially the Daciflst\ngroup represented by the National Coun\ncil for Prevention of War. Mr. Hoover\ngoes no farther, with reference to the\nWorld Court, than he went when ad\ndressing the Daughters of the Ameri\ncan Revolution last April. On that oc\ncasion he acclaimed the court, men\ntioned the \"contention\u201d over the \u201cspe-\ncial stipulations\u201d under which America\nwould join it, and predicted that \u201cthe j\nUnited States will some time become a\nmember.\u201d\nAlmost as noteworthy as the Presl-\ndent's silence about further steps to\ntake this country into the World Court\nLs his outspoken unwillingness, amid\npresent world conditions, to pin his i\nwhole faith in instruments like the Kel-\nlogg pact as a guarantee of peace.\nFuture Held Doubtful.\nDespite the Increase in Democratic\nstrength in the Senate, as result of the\nrecent elections, there is serious doubt\nwhether the White House can count\nany more confidently on a two-thirds\nratification vote for the World Court\nthan it could in the past. .The old ir\nreconcilable bloc is still irreconcilable\nand musters enough support on both\nthe Republican and Democratic sides of\nthe Senate to hold up ratification. A\nvery influential member of the Foreign\nRelations Committee now in Washing\nton is of opinion that the immediate\noutlook for the court is Just as bleak\ntoday as it has been during all the\nseven years since President Harding\nfirst asked the Senate to authorize our\nentry. Even the new era of \"coalition,\u201d\nthe Senator in question says, holds out,\nin his opinion, little hope of ratifica\ntion. In congressional circles there is\na little surprise that President Hoover\nstill hesitates to demand Senat** action\non the court, though the same quarters\ncredit him with \u201cgood political sense\u201d\nin not doing so at this time.\nMenace In Europe Seen.\nFriends of preparedness read into the\ncarefully phrased Hoover sentiments in\nthe Armistice day speech a readiness on\nthe part of the administration to seek\nprompt action on behalf of the \"treaty\nnavy\u201d authorized at the London Con\nference. No other construction, it ls\ncontended, can be placed on the Presi\ndent\u2019s references to the \u201cdangers which\nforeign wars bring to our shores.\u201d\nMr. Hoover, in the same paragraph\nof his address, directly hints at Amer\nica\u2019s necessity to bear In. mind what\nshe may be called upon to do in her\nown defense, in case the other nations\nof the frorld go to war in spite of all\nthe safeguards set up to prevent it.\nBoiled down to plain terms. President\nHoover defines his idea of America\u2019s\npeace policy at this hour as follows:\n\u201cMaintain our faith in the various in\nstrumentalities established for preser\nvation of peace, but keep our powder\ndry and our sword sharp for possible\nuse in the event that these instrumen\ntalities fail of their purpose.\u201d It is an\nopen secret that the Washington ad\nministration looks at present-hour in\nternational conditions, especially in Eu\nrope, as full of menace. To the extent\nof his powers, President Hoover would\nlend American influence to the easing\nof the situation \u201cover there.\u201d\nBut it is apparent from the Armistice i\nday address that meantime the Quaker j\nChief Executive of the United States j\nintends to remain on what that other i\nengineer President, George Washington,\nI in the farewell address termed \u201ca re\nspectable defensive posture.\u201d\n(Copyrl\u00dfht. 3930.)\nBuy Now-For Better Times\nI, rLest We Forget\" If you need tilings\ni n Ky why wait? \u2014Do\na no^ cr yourself a good\nW* 11 tU1 n a\n1 v e r a tcl cr n thing\u2014Buy Now!\ns i\u00bb cC fur o-\nCea \\w vaSt J A\"\nf t\u00ab 0 1 yea S 7r Pr CeS re Rights\neVe o\\p o \\p flfl Values are Great!\nj\u00a3l** 9\nSQCt\nnJ\n*o/J Art \u2019st s f\nr 7 n \u2019t e Q\nrrn \u2019s t Ce a n u T one on th\u00ab\n9^ a,n D J. te Pr 0 popular Kaufman\nBudget Plan.\nS C\u00b0; n Cash Balance 10\nu weekly or live l /2\nev \u00b0ir lt 7\ntJlajUo faf** monthly payments.\nHome of Smith Smart Shoes\nWAR MOTHERS FLY OLD GLORY\nt- .in j ~k\ni\nl W\u00ae fei\\ y V 'T; v *j\nv v -\u00bbT*\n\nfV\nI\n\n\n\n\u25a0M j/\nJfc wm\nmm \\Mm JK, Jm\nH| mb ad\u00ab\nl 2H\n\nThe District Chapter of the American War Mother* raise* a flag on the\nCapitol. They are, left to right: Admiral R. E. Coontz, 17. S. N.. retired; Miss\nWinifred Nichols, Mr*. M. C. O\u2019Neil, Mr*. Ella Chambers, Calvin P, Howerin,\nHarry Wilson, Carl Evers, Charles Williams, George B. Hurr and Charles\nThomashopski. \u2014Star Staff Photo.\nGEN. LEJEUNE TO TALK\nTO ALUMNI OF V. M. I.\nFifth Head of School to Be Gue\u00bbt\nat Founders\u2019 Day Smoker\nHere.\nMaj. Gen. John A. Lejeune, retired\ncommandant of the United States Ma\nrine Corps and superintendent of the\ni Virginia Military Institute, will be the\nprincipal speaker\nand guest of honor\nat the informal\nsmoker of the V.\nM. I. Alumni Asso\nciation, commemo\nrating Founders\u2019 i\nday, tonight at the\nArmy and Navy\nClub.\nSeveral old ca\ndets and friends of\nthe institute, which\nwas founded 91\nyears ago today,\nwill speak at the 8\no\u2019clock meeting to\nnight.\nGen. Lejeune is\nthe fifth superin\ntendent of V. M. 1.,\n4#\nGen.\nthe other heads of the institute includ\ning Gens. Smith, Shipp, Nichols and\nCocke.\nVeteran Prospector Dies.\nOTTAWA, November 11 OP).\u2014John j\nJ. McDermott, veteran prospector of i\nNorthern Ontario, who played a part\ni In establishing the Hollinger gold mine,\ndied at a hotel here yesterday.\n\u2022GERALDINE FARRAR\nADVISES \u201cTALKIE\u201d\ni\nSends Young Singers to Hollywood,\nbut Refuses to Trust Radio\nHerself.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, November 11\u2014Ger\naldine Farrar advises the Nation's\nyoung singers to go to Hollywood and\ncast their talents before the talkies.\n\u201cDo not waste your freshness and\nyouth as a mere gadget in a Ford estab\nlishment such as the Metropolitan\nOpera House.\u201d she is quoted by today\u2019s\nNew York Times. \u201cGo to Hollywood\ni and make the most of your youth, with\nquick returns in the talkies.\u201d\nAt the same time the former Metro-\nSjlitan prima donna declined to prac\nce her preaching and stated she never i\nwould sing for the sound films or the\nradio.\nWILLIAM KETTNER DIES\nFormer Representative Active for\nBoulder Dam Project. 1\nSAN DIEGO, Calif., November 11 (A 5\n\u2014William Kettner, 66, San Diego busi\nness man and former Representative\nfrom the eleventh California district,\ndied today of hrart disease.\nKettner was one of the leaders in the\nearly campaign for the Boulder Dam\nproject. He served in Congress from\n1913 to 1921.\nj\nClock golf and bowling are being pro\ni vided for members of the British Par\ni liament.\ni\nTONIGHT!\nEnjoy the Best Dollar Dinner\nIN WASHINGTON\nEverything Fresh No Left-Overt Used\nNote: If you ever ate a better Dollar Dinner, you need not pay the check!\nr.im\nI (VI\nTuesday, November 11, 1930\nDinner One Dollar I\ne\nFresh Shrimp and Pineapple Cocktail\nCream of Tomato Soup\nChicken Consomme With Rice\nRelishes and Conserves\nT I Broiled Halibut With Lemon Rinrs\nServed southern Fried Chicken Served\nHam Baked In Cider\nrom Veal Cutlet With Mushrooms from\n5 to 8:30 Fresh Vegetable Dinner 5 to 8:30\no\u2019clock Fresh string: Beans Buttered Beets o\u2019clock\nMashed Potato\nJohnny Cake Hot Tea Biscuit\nLettuce With Roquefort Dressing\nMocha Layer Cake Apple Pie\nBread and Butter Pudding With Cream\nPumpkin Tart Orange Fruit Jelly\nFresh Pineapple Sundae\nAmerican Cheese With Toasted Crackers\nVanilla, Peach, Chocolate or\nBurnt Almond Ice Cream\nRaspberry Sherbet\nHappiness Restaurant\n1107 F STREET N.W.\n.'.T II V I\n>S)\nPRESIDENT LAUDS\nWORK OF AD' MEN\nHoover Stays After Speech\n\nto Hear Election Returns\nInterpreted.\nPresident Hoover last night told the\nAssociation of National Advertisers in\nconvention here that their copy can\nbeguile business from its lethargy, cre\nate demand and stimulate production\nand distribution and then, contrary to\nhis usual custom, sat among the ad\nvertiser* while David Lawrence, pub\nlisher of the United States Dally, inter\npreted last Tuesday\u2019s election as an\nexpression from the people of the\nUnited States in favor of legislative\nco-operation between both parties in\nthe next Congress.\nThe President and Mr. Lawrence\nspoke from the banquet board of the\nadvertisers in the ball room of the\nWardman Park Hotel, climaxing the\nfirst day\u2019s sessions of the twenty-first\nannual convention of repreaentativea\nof firms paying one-fifth of the Nation's\nadvertising bill annually. Both ad\ndresses were broadcast over a Nation\nwide network of the National Broad\ncasting Co.\nThe President was Introduced by\nj Bernard Ltchtenberg, president of the\nassociation and toastmaster at last\nnight\u2019s meeting.\nHoover's Address.\nThe President's address follows:\n\u201cIt gives me great pleasure to ex\ntend greeting to you upon your assembly\nin Washington. Advertising is one of\nthe vital organs of our entire economic\nand social system. It certainly is the\nvocal organ by which industry sings its\nsongs of beguilement. The purpose of\nadvertising is to create desire, and from\nthe torments of desire there at once\nemerges additional demand and from\ndemand you pull upon Increasing pro\nauction and distribution. By the stimu-\nlants of advertising which you ad-\nminister you have stirred the lethargy\nof the old law of supply and demand 1\nuntil you have transformed oottage\nindustries into mass production. From j\nenlarged diffusion of articles and ser-\nvices you cheapen costs and thereby i\nyou are a part of the dynamic force\nwhich creates high standards of living, j\n\u201cYou also contribute to hurry up the\ngeneral use of every discovery in science\nand every invention in industry. It\nprobably required a thousand years to\nspread the knowledge and application\nof that great human invention, the\nwheeled cart, and it has taken you only\n20 years to make the automobile the\nuniversal tool of man. Moreover, your\nconstant exploitation of every improve-\nment in every article and service\nspreads a restless pillow for every com\npetitor and drives the producer to\nfeverish exertions in new invention,\nnew service, and still more Improve\nment. Incidentally, you make possible\nthe vast distribution of information, of\ngood cheer and tribulation which comes\nj with the morning paper, the periodical, I\nand the radio. And your contributions\nto them aids to sustain a great army\n|of authors and artists who could not\notherwise join in the standards of living\ni you create.\nI \u201cYour latest contribution to con\ni structlve joy Is to make possible the\ni hourly spread of music, entertainment,\nand political assertion to the radio sets\n:in 12.0G0.000 homes.\nLooked Upon as Intrusion.\n\u201cAt one time advertising was per\nhaps looked upon as an intrusion, a\nclamor to the credulous. But your\nsubtlety and beguiling methods have\nlong since overcome this resentment.\nFrom all of which the public has\nceased to deny the usefulness of ad\nvertising and has come to include you\nIn the things we bear In life.\n\u201cBut In more serious turn, the very\nimportance of the position which ad\nvertising has risen to occupy in the\neconomic system is in direct proportion\nto the ability of the people to depend\nupon the probity of the statements you\npresent. The advertising executive and j\nthe medium through which he ad- j\nvertlses must see to it that the desire j\nyou create Is satisfied by the article\nrecommended. The good will of the j\npublic toward the producer, the goods,\nor the service is the essential of sound\nadvertising\u2014for no business succeeds\nupon the sale of an article once. Ani\nto maintain this confidence of the pub-\nHe you and the mediums which sou\npatronise have an l*tersst that others\ndo not violate confidence and thereby\ndiscredit the whole of advertising.\n\u201cYou have recognised that responsi\nbility The Setter Business Bureau and\nthe vigilance agencies which you ha vs\nset up to safeguard the general reputa\ntion of advertising are not only sound\nethics, but sound business. In the polic\ning of your own business you are con-\ntributlng soundly to self-government\nby curing abuse without the interfer\nence of Government. I wish you success\nin your convention and in the purposes\nfor which you are assembled.\u201d\nLawrence's Speech.\nCalled upon by the advertiser* to\ninterpret the meaning of last Tues\nday\u2019s election in terms of current busi\nness, Mr. Lawrence said, in part:\n\u201cThe simple answer might be that\nboth political parties are equally in\nterested in developing for this coun\ntry a return of prosperity, and hence\nthat nothing will be done to injure\n'legitimate' Industry. But If there should\nbe a difference of opinion between Con\ngress and the Executive as to whether\na piece of legislation Is harmful to busl-\nness and if it should go to the White\nHouse for action, it is well to bear In\nmind that the President of the United\nStates can. if he likes, exercise the veto\npower. Republicans and Democrats, for\nthe most part, arc Just the same under\nthe skin. Announcement of the leader*\nof both pa-ties that they desire an era\nof co-operr.tion Is significant.\n\u201cIt doe-, not mean that these political\nleaders have suddenly become Imbued\nwith a desire to be non-partisan. It does\nmean that these political leaders are\nresponsive to what they know to be a\nserious mood of the country. It wants\nthe Government to function smoothlv\nand constructively, for this is a period\nof great emergency, a crisis unparalleled\nin world history. We forget party lines\nand unite when human lives are In\njeopardy on the field of battle. It mav\nbe that we are capable of uniting in\na common cause when human misery\nI is so widespread.\u201d\n\nMOVIE OWNERS INDORSE\n\u201cBUY-NOW\u201d CAMPAIGN\n\nExtravagant Spending Is What\nCountry Needs, Declares Former\nHead of Organization.\n1 By the Associated Pres*.\nI PHILADELPHIA, November ll.\u2014ln\ndorsement of the national \u201cBuy Now\u201d\ncampaign as a means of starting busi\nness on the upgrade, was voted y ester\nday by the Motion Picture Theater\nOwners of America at the opening of\ntheir annual convention.\nM. A. Lightner, president of the\norganization, appointed a committee to\nconsider the best methods of further\ning the campaign throughtout the\ncountry.\nThe \u201cBuy Now\u201d proposal brought a\nj criticism of certain bankers by R. P.\nWoodhull, a former president. \u201cThe\nbankers.\u201d he said, \u201care responsible for\nthe thrifty habits of the people. Even\nnow they ask us to spend wisely. That\nIs foolishness. What this country needs\nla extravagant spending. We never had\nprosperity until the people had learned\nto spend extravagantly and bought\nthings they didn't need.\u201d\nELECTION DAY DELAYED\nSpain Unable to Choose Parliament\nBefore March 1.\nMADRID, November 11 (IP). \u2014Spain\u2019s\nparliamentary election, the first since\n1923, when Primo de Rivera established\nthe dictatorship, cannot be held before\nMarch 1, Ossorio Gallardo, head of the\nCentral Census Board, announced yes\nterday, because of inability to complete\nthe electorial census much before that\ndate.\nThe Census Board, created to study\nelectoral conditions, is expected to re\nport its findings to the cabinet next\nTuesday and thereafter a definite,\nelection date will be set. The cabinet\nalso must decide whether municipal\nelection will precede the parliamentary\nvoting.\nGalsworthy to Make Lecture Tour.\nNEW YORK, November 11\nj John Galsworthy, English writer, will\nspend the coming Winter in Arizona,\nafter which he will lecture in eight\ncities, nis American representatives an-\nI nounced today. Mrs. Galsworthy will\naccompany him.\nf I","height":"25341","width":"19743"}}
